50|$|In 1936, {{she left}} her post at the Maryland League of Women Voters and was {{appointed}} by Franklin Delano Roosevelt to the <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> Administration, where she served until her retirement in 1966. She first acted as an educational representative, traveling the country to speak at college campuses and women's boards, but was soon promoted to Chief of Field Operations. In 1942, she was appointed Director of Region III, and in 1951, she became Assistant to the Commissioner of <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> in <b>charge</b> of staff development. In 1963, she joined the Welfare Administration.|$|R
